From: scottge1@limestone.uucp (George M. Scott)
Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
Subject: Re: Hurd status and call for volunteers
Date: 5 Nov 1993 19:57:10 GMT

In article <1993Nov4.222352.26988@super.org> becker@super.org (Donald J. Becker) writes:
>
>I used to think that a microkernel would allow easy development with only a
>slight loss in performance.  I now know that the hard parts of driver
>development are the "thinking" and "actually writing it" phases, not the
>"putting it into the kernel" part.  Add to this the evidence that microkernels
>are significantly slower than monolithic kernels, and microkernels don't make
>a lot of sense.

Apparently you haven't heard of Brian "Performance" Bershad's work at
CMU.  May I direct your attention to mach.cs.cmu.edu:/usr/mach/public/doc
for many papers on the performance of microkernels (actually just mach).
You may want to read the papers with "Performance" in the title.

Actually, drivers do not have to be present in the kernel (other than disk
and terminal support).  The rest may be dynamically loaded as is done
in AIX 3.X.X.  I hope that eventually Mach will be modified so that
it will have this feature.  It makes for a smaller kernel, since you
do not have a kernel that supports 100 devices you do not have.  Nor do
you have to rebuild the kernel if you add a new device, just toss it in
the proper directory and the kernel will take care of it at boot time.
Convenient, eh?

George

-- 
George Scott
Michigan State University
scottge1@cps.msu.edu

