Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
From: mhcoffin@tolstoy.uwaterloo.ca (Michael Coffin)
Subject: Re: Hurd status and call for volunteers
Date: Fri, 5 Nov 1993 19:41:08 GMT

In article <1993Nov5.124815.8760@vlsi.polymtl.ca> hallu@info.polymtl.ca (Louis-D. Dubeau) writes:

   Well, acroding to studies by CMU a microkernel -- server
   combinasion is not that slower. In the article "Unix as an
   Application Program" (you can get it on mach.cs.cmu.edu), they show
   that Mach 3.0 with a Unix server is faster than SunOS 4.0 (they
   were run on a Sun 3/60) in the compilation test and is 3% slower in
   the file system test.

But, but, but...

Sun OS is horrifyingly slow.  Their file system is painful.  I use a
Sparc2 at work and Linux at home.  Although the raw speed of the two
machines is not terribly different (the Sun is a little faster on most
CPU benchmarks), the Linux machine is infinitely more responsive than
the Sun even with less memory.  It's like night and day.

These kind of comparisons remind of the days when everyone compared
their fancy new C compilers to pcc and bragged about what wonderful
optimizers they had.  It'll be a cold day in hell when I switch to a
file system 3% slower than Sun's.

-mike

